result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (5th or 6th) and Operating w/ PAC (5th or 6th). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (5th or 6th) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (5th or 6th) was dismissed by the court.

  • Brian S Palmquist was found guilty of OWI (5th or 6th), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

superMiscConds.notes:
Pay $600.00 fine plus costs and Department of Corrections Supervision fees.  If the defendant is discharged from Extended Supervision with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment may be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and governmental entities for the balance due.
------------------------------

Maintain full time employment or education unless in a treatment program.
------------------------------

Not to possess a firearm or pocket knife unless required for work.
------------------------------

No alcohol. Not to operate a motor vehicle without a valid license. Not to operate a motor vehicle unless properly equipped with IID. Not to enter any bars, liquor stores, or premises whose primary function is the sale of alcohol.
------------------------------

Must attend a Victim Impact Panel.   Counseling as recommended by Probation Agent. Must take all medications as prescribed for mental health.  Provide biological specimen to state crime lab for DNA analysis, and pay DNA analysis surcharge.
